[1] Citrus County, Florida
Date: Wed 24 Jul 2019
Source: ABC [edited]
https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/region-citrus-hernando/flesh-eating-bacteria-possibly-traveled-through-mans-needle-puncture-nearly-killing-him


A Citrus County man who is among the latest to contract flesh-eating bacteria (the cause of necrotizing fasciitis - Mod.LL) says he is grateful to be alive. When he contracted necrotizing fasciitis, he didn't show symptoms for several weeks.

ABC Action News reporter Michael Paluska talked to the man from his Citrus County home. After spending nearly 2 weeks in the hospital, he was able to return home on 11 Jul 2019. The man and his wife vacationed in the Panhandle [of Florida] in late May 2019. Before the trip, the man said he got shots for pain in his lower back and buttocks. "It got in, possibly, most likely through this slight little tiny injection site where the steroids were put in. The bacteria got in through those pinhole-type injections," he said.

After returning home, the patient said he felt a little discomfort. However, weeks later he knew something was wrong. "When it got to be like the size of a lemon inside one of my butt cheeks, it was a sign something wasn't right," he said. "I could feel this like an abscess-type thing forming on my bottom, really inflamed, hot, and very swollen."

If he didn't decide to go to Citrus Memorial Hospital when he did, doctors don't think he would've survived. "They operated 6 days straight; 6 consecutive days had surgeries to make sure they got everything out. It spread to my pelvis," he said. "They cut me from here to here, and they took my digestive system out and inspected it to make sure there was nothing necrotizing on it and then put it all back in."

The man, 68, said he doesn't have an autoimmune disease and never thought his body wouldn't be able to fight off the infection. Now he wants to raise awareness for anyone swimming with an open wound or [who] recently was vaccinated or got a shot. "It could happen to anybody; it's made me aware of my mortality, that life is precious. You don't know you are just going to go swimming and maybe not make it. Something could happen; we don't know," he said. "If you are thinking of going swimming and you have a little tiny cut, maybe think twice about going."

[Byline: Michael Paluska]

